aa(lp51
VMy kind of eureka moment came a few years later,
p52
aVwhen I was studying the art of the courts of Northern Europe,
p53
aVand of course it was very much discussed in terms of
p54
aVthe paintings and the sculptures
p55
aVand the architecture of the day.
p56
aVBut as I began to read historical documents
p57
aVand contemporary descriptions,
p58
aVI found there was a kind of a missing component,
p59
aVfor everywhere I came across descriptions of tapestries.
p60
aVTapestries were ubiquitous between the Middle Ages
p61
aVand, really, well into the 18th century,
p62
aVand it was pretty apparent why.
p63
aVTapestries were portable. You could roll them up,
p64
aVsend them ahead of you, and in the time
p65
aVit took to hang them up, you could transform a cold,
p66
aVdank interior into a richly colored setting.
p67
aVTapestries effectively provided a vast canvas
p68
aVon which the patrons of the day could depict the heroes
p69
aVwith whom they wanted to be associated,
p70
aVor even themselves,
p71
aVand in addition to that, tapestries were hugely expensive.
p72
aVThey required scores of highly skilled weavers
p73
aVworking over extended periods of time
p74
aVwith very expensive materials \u2014 the wools, the silks,
p75
aVeven gold and silver thread.
p76
aVSo, all in all, in an age when the visual image
p77
aVof any kind was rare, tapestries were an incredibly potent
p78
aVform of propaganda.
