aa(lp80
VWell, I became a tapestry historian.
p81
aVIn due course, I ended up as a curator
p82
aVat the Metropolitan Museum, because I saw the Met
p83
aVas one of the few places where I could organize
p84
aVreally big exhibitions about the subject
p85
aVI cared so passionately about.
p86
aVAnd in about 1997, the then-director Philippe de Montebello
p87
aVgave me the go-ahead to organize an exhibition
p88
aVfor 2002. We normally have these very long lead-in times.
p89
aa(lp90
VIt wasn't straightforward. It's no longer a question
p91
aVof chucking a tapestry in the back of a car.
p92
aVThey have to be wound on huge rollers,
p93
aVshipped in oversized freighters.
p94
aVSome of them are so big we had, to get them into the museum,
p95
aVwe had to take them up the great steps at the front.
